<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1218,2004]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,1218,1244]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
A member of the 
<taxonomicName box="[499,785,1219,1244]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigricans">
<emphasis box="[499,785,1219,1244]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Leptotyphlops nigricans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. Differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Boulenger" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[1127,1232,1219,1244]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kafubi">
<emphasis box="[1127,1232,1219,1244]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">L. kafubi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its fused parietal bones, lower middorsal counts and having the nostril separated from the rostral by a longer suture.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="34" lastPageNumber="35" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1218,2004]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,350,1298,1324]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Description.</emphasis>
Body cylindrical, with head and neck broadened and flattened, the short tail tapers slightly before a small spine or blunt tail cone.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1218,2004]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Snout rounded, rostral moderate (0.43–0.53 head width, mean = 0.46), truncated posteriorly, much wider than nasals and extending to a line connecting centre of eyes, a preoral groove present ventrally. Behind rostral, upper lip bordered by infranasal (nostril midway between rostral and supralabial along nasal suture), small anterior supralabial that reaches level of nostril with a width along lip 2.0–3.0 times that of infranasal, large ocular with eye central in upper half, and large posterior supralabial. Supraoculars pentagonal, slightly larger than the hexagonal frontal and postfrontal, which are slightly smaller than the interparietal and interoccipital (note that the postfrontal is fused wuith the interparietal in the 
<typeStatus box="[960,1073,1618,1644]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">lectotype</typeStatus>
). Parietals oblique, subequal to the fused occipitals, in contact with the posterior supralabial. Temporal single. No mental.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1218,2004]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Body covered with 14 rows of smooth, imbricate, subequal scales. Reduction to 10 rows on the tail takes place lateral to the subtriangular cloacal shield. Total middorsals 198–244; subcaudals 20–32.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1218,2004]" box="[198,963,1778,1804]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Total length/diameter ratio 38–74; total length/tail ratio 8.1–15.3.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1218,2004]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Dorsum and venter uniformly dark brown to black, except upper lip, chin, and cloacal shield which are white.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1218,2004]" box="[198,991,1898,1924]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Skull with fused parietal bones as in 
<taxonomicName box="[630,772,1899,1924]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigricans">
<emphasis box="[630,772,1899,1924]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">L. nigricans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[787,872,1898,1924]" captionStart="PLATE 4" captionStartId="11.[151,238,1626,1650]" captionTargetBox="[307,1289,197,1614]" captionTargetId="figure-257@11.[263,1331,162,1634]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="PLATE 4. Figure 1. Dorsal views of the skulls of Leptotyphlops. A. Leptotyphlops nigricans (MCZ 21473) and B. Leptotyphlops kafubi (FMNH 56374), both after List (1966). KEY to bone abbreviations from List, 1966: Ax = axis, At = atlas, Eo = exoccipital, F = frontal, M = maxilla, N = nasal, P = parietal, Pf = prefrontal, Po = prootic, So = supraoccipital. C. Leptotyphlops cairi, after Abdeen et al. (1991). KEY to bone abbreviations from Abdeen et al., 1991: B.OC. = basioccipital; B.SP. = basisphenoid; C.T.C. = cartilaginouis trebacula cranii; EX.OC. = exoccipital; FR. = frontal; L.P.P.MX. = lateral process of maxilla; MX. = maxilla; NA. = nasal; OC.CO. = occipital condyle; P.MX. = premaxilla; P.OT. = prootic; P.VO. = prevomer; PA. = palatine; PR. = parietal; PR.FR. = prefrontal; PR.L.DG. = lateral downgrowth of parietal; PT. = pterygoid; S.OC. = supraoccipital. The lines represent 1 mm to scale. The stipple indicates thin transparent membrane. Figure 2. Dorsal views of the skulls of Leptotyphlops. A. Leptotyphlops nigroterminus sp. nov. (ZMB 51610); B. Leptotyphlops macrurus (BMNH 1957.1.10.26); C. Leptotyphlops boulengeri (MCZ 40087); D. Leptotyphlops reticulatus (BMNH 1954.1.12.77). E. Leptotyphlops longicaudus (NMZB-UM 29371); F. Leptotyphlops blanfordii (BMNH 1977.833); G. Leptotyphlops nursii (FMNH 66158). H. Leptotyphlops scutifrons merkeri (NMZB 8089). The lines represent 1 mm to scale. KEY: f = frontal; n = nasal; p = parietal; pp = postparietal; so = supraoccipital." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6789072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6789072/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Plate 4</figureCitation>
, Fig. 1A).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1218,2004]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,256,1938,1964]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Size.</emphasis>
Largest specimen (NMZB 14334 — Kyambura Game Reserve, Ankole, 
<collectingCountry box="[1137,1230,1938,1964]" name="Uganda" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Uganda</collectingCountry>
) 152 + 13 = 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="165.0">165 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1437,151,1018]" box="[198,416,151,178]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,302,151,177]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Habitat.</emphasis>
Savanna.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1437,151,1018]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,319,191,217]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1890" box="[328,525,192,217]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Glauconia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="emini">
<emphasis box="[328,525,192,217]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Glauconia emini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was based on 
<specimenCount box="[700,858,192,218]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="generic" typeStatus="syntypes">two syntypes</specimenCount>
, but BM 1946.1.10.86 was lost in the post on its way from London to 
<collectingRegion box="[407,529,232,258]" country="Zimbabwe" name="Bulawayo" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Bulawayo</collectingRegion>
, so BM 1946.1.10.87, the specimen illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Boulenger" box="[1131,1343,232,258]" firstAuthor="Boulenger" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="1 - 38" refId="ref57270" refString="Boulenger, G. A. (1893) Catalogue of the Snakes in the British Museum (Natural History), Volume I, containing the families Typhlopidae, Glauconiidae, Boidae, Ilysiidae, Uropeltidae, Xenopeltidae, and Colubridae aglyphae, part. British Museum (Natural History), London, xiii + 448 pp., Pls. 1 - 38." type="book chapter" year="1893">Boulenger (1893)</bibRefCitation>
, is here nominated 
<typeStatus box="[284,395,272,298]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">lectotype</typeStatus>
. It should be pointed out that this specimen is aberrant in having the postfrontal fused with the interparietal. Two additional specimens, BM 91.4.30.1 (A &amp; B) from Nyamkolo on Lake Tanganyika, were assigned to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1890" box="[354,451,352,377]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Glauconia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="emini">
<emphasis box="[354,451,352,377]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">G. emini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Boulenger in 1893, but the second of these has the frontal fused with the rostral, which led Broadley to tentatively assign it to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Jan" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[685,843,392,417]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="conjunctus">
<emphasis box="[685,843,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">L. conjunctus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 1976. We now consider this to be another aberrant 
<emphasis box="[203,306,432,457]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1890" box="[203,301,432,457]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Glauconia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="emini">L. emini</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and this species was subsequently collected by 
<bibRefCitation author="Loveridge" box="[862,1067,432,458]" firstAuthor="Loveridge" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="197 - 416" refId="ref60588" refString="Loveridge, A. (1933) Reports on the scientific results of an expedition to the southwestern highlands of Tanganyika Territory. VII. Herpetology. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College (Cambridge), 74 (7), 197 - 416, Pls. 1 - 3." type="journal article" year="1933">Loveridge (1933)</bibRefCitation>
at Kitungulu, only 
<quantity box="[1293,1367,432,458]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" unit="km" value="40.0">40 km</quantity>
north of Nyamkolo.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1437,151,1018]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
NMZB 14334 from Kyambura Game Reserve in southwest 
<collectingCountry box="[902,993,512,538]" name="Uganda" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Uganda</collectingCountry>
is unusual in having a very large rostral which is truncated posteriorly, together with the nasals, at the level of the eyes; in addition the enlarged anterior supralabial excludes the infranasal from the lip. A typical 
<taxonomicName box="[933,1171,592,617]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="emini">
<emphasis box="[933,1171,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Leptotyphlops emini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was taken at the same locality.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
